"""
A Linda-style shared tuple space for concurrent coordination.

TupleSpace stores tuples (any Maggie objects) and retrieves them by
matching against CUE templates. Operations can be blocking (in:, read:)
or non-blocking (tryIn:, tryRead:). Blocking operations suspend the
current process until a matching tuple is available.

Tuples are matched using CUE unification: a template is a CueValue,
and a tuple matches if projecting it into CUE and unifying with the
template produces no error (no bottom).

Tuples have three modes:
  - Linear (default): consumed exactly once by in:
  - Persistent: never consumed; in: returns a copy but keeps the original
  - Affine: consumed at most once, can expire via TTL

```test
ts := TupleSpace new.
ts isEmpty >>> true
ts out: 42.
ts size >>> 1
ts isEmpty >>> false
```
"""
TupleSpace subclass: Object

  """
  Publish a tuple into the space. Non-blocking. If a process is
  blocked waiting for a matching tuple (via in: or read:), it will
  be woken immediately. The tuple is stored in linear mode (consumed
  exactly once by in:).

  ```test
  ts := TupleSpace new.
  ts out: 42.
  ts out: 'hello'.
  ts size >>> 2
  ```
  """
  method: out: aTuple ! <Process> [
      ^self primOut: aTuple
  ]

  """
  Publish a persistent tuple into the space. Persistent tuples are
  never consumed by in: -- reads return the value but the tuple
  stays in the space. Useful for shared facts and blackboard knowledge.

  ```test
  ts := TupleSpace new.
  ctx := CueContext new.
  intTmpl := (ctx compileString: 'int') value.
  ts outPersistent: 42.
  ts tryIn: intTmpl >>> 42
  ts size >>> 1
  ts tryIn: intTmpl >>> 42
  ts size >>> 1
  ```
  """
  method: outPersistent: aTuple ! <Process> [
      ^self primOutPersistent: aTuple
  ]

  """
  Publish an affine tuple with a time-to-live in milliseconds.
  The tuple is automatically removed after the TTL expires if not
  consumed first. Expired tuples are lazily cleaned during scans.

  ```example
  | ts <TupleSpace> |
  ts := TupleSpace new.
  ts outAffine: 'ephemeral offer' ttl: 5000.
  ```
  """
  method: outAffine: aTuple ttl: milliseconds <Integer> ! <Process> [
      ^self primOutAffine: aTuple ttl: milliseconds
  ]

  """
  Publish a tuple that is automatically removed when the given
  CancellationContext is cancelled. The tuple behaves as linear
  until cancellation.

  ```example
  | ts <TupleSpace> ctx <CancellationContext> |
  ts := TupleSpace new.
  ctx := CancellationContext withCancel.
  ts out: 'resource' withContext: ctx.
  ctx cancel.
  ```
  """
  method: out: aTuple withContext: aContext <CancellationContext> ! <Process> [
      ^self primOut: aTuple withContext: aContext
  ]

  """
  Take the first tuple matching the CUE template. Blocks until a
  matching tuple is available. The tuple is removed from the space
  (destructive read / linear consumption).

  For persistent tuples, the value is returned but the tuple stays
  in the space (non-destructive).

  The template must be a CueValue. Use CueContext>>compileString:
  to create templates.

  ```example
  | ts <TupleSpace> ctx <CueContext> |
  ts := TupleSpace new.
  ctx := CueContext new.
  [ts out: 42] fork.
  ts in: (ctx compileString: 'int') value
  ```
  """
  method: in: aTemplate <CueValue> ! <Process> [
      ^self primIn: aTemplate
  ]

  """
  Read the first tuple matching the CUE template. Blocks until a
  matching tuple is available. The tuple remains in the space
  (non-destructive read).

  ```example
  | ts <TupleSpace> ctx <CueContext> |
  ts := TupleSpace new.
  ctx := CueContext new.
  ts out: 42.
  ts read: (ctx compileString: 'int') value
  ```
  """
  method: read: aTemplate <CueValue> ! <Process> [
      ^self primRead: aTemplate
  ]

  """
  Try to take a matching tuple without blocking. Returns the tuple
  if found (and removes it), or nil if no match.

  ```test
  ts := TupleSpace new.
  ctx := CueContext new.
  intTmpl := (ctx compileString: 'int') value.
  ts tryIn: intTmpl >>> nil
  ts out: 42.
  ts tryIn: intTmpl >>> 42
  ts size >>> 0
  ```
  """
  method: tryIn: aTemplate <CueValue> [
      ^self primTryIn: aTemplate
  ]

  """
  Try to read a matching tuple without blocking. Returns the tuple
  if found (does not remove it), or nil if no match.

  ```test
  ts := TupleSpace new.
  ctx := CueContext new.
  intTmpl := (ctx compileString: 'int') value.
  ts tryRead: intTmpl >>> nil
  ts out: 42.
  ts tryRead: intTmpl >>> 42
  ts size >>> 1
  ```
  """
  method: tryRead: aTemplate <CueValue> [
      ^self primTryRead: aTemplate
  ]

  """
  Atomically take ALL tuples matching an array of templates.
  Blocks until all templates are simultaneously satisfiable.
  Each template must match a DIFFERENT tuple.

  This is the tensor product from linear logic -- it prevents
  the classic coordination bug where an agent takes a task but
  the required resource was grabbed between two separate in: calls.

  Returns an Array of results in the same order as the templates.

  ```example
  | ts <TupleSpace> ctx <CueContext> |
  ts := TupleSpace new.
  ctx := CueContext new.
  ts out: 42.
  ts out: 'hello'.
  ts inAll: {(ctx compileString: 'int') value. (ctx compileString: 'string') value}
  ```
  """
  method: inAll: templateArray <Array> ^<Array> ! <Process> [
      ^self primInAll: templateArray
  ]

  """
  Take whichever tuple matches first from an array of templates.
  Scans tuples and returns the first match from any template.
  If none match, blocks until any one does.

  This is the additive disjunction from linear logic -- like
  Channel select: but for tuple templates.

  ```example
  | ts <TupleSpace> ctx <CueContext> |
  ts := TupleSpace new.
  ctx := CueContext new.
  ts out: 42.
  ts inAny: {(ctx compileString: 'int') value. (ctx compileString: 'string') value}
  ```
  """
  method: inAny: templateArray <Array> ! <Process> [
      ^self primInAny: templateArray
  ]

  """
  Return the number of tuples currently stored.

  ```test
  ts := TupleSpace new.
  ts size >>> 0
  ts out: 1.
  ts out: 2.
  ts size >>> 2
  ```
  """
  method: size ^<Integer> [
      ^self primSize
  ]

  """
  Return true if the space contains no tuples.

  ```test
  ts := TupleSpace new.
  ts isEmpty >>> true
  ts out: 1.
  ts isEmpty >>> false
  ```
  """
  method: isEmpty ^<Boolean> [
      ^self primIsEmpty
  ]

  """
  Return a human-readable description.
  """
  method: printString ^<String> [
      ^self primPrintString
  ]
